# Chapter 5: Professions
___
Right, let me make this clear. Professions, in my mind, have three parts:

1) The base rules/system. Anyone can use these to make items, and only using these indicates that a person has a passing interest in the profession. May or may not be related to a particular tool/skill proficiency.
2) A dedicated feat for each profession, similar to the UA feats for specific skills (Gourmand, Arcanist, Performer, etc.). These provide benefits related to the profession, such as being able to craft items faster and more efficiently, some side benefits related to your expertise, and so on. This indicates someone who has had some specific training in the profession.
3) A profession [name pending] in the Artisan class. Not a subclass with unique skills tied to each profession...probably... but a particular focus on one or more skills or tools. This comes with benefits on top of the feat for that profession (may just be that you get bonus feats that are the profession feats, it's all up in the air right now). A person who takes the Artisan class isn't just a dabbler--this is what they do full time and thus they have the greatest abilities related to the profession.

\pagebreakNum

# Chapter 6: Variant Rules
## Silver Standard
If the cost was in copper, its price does not change.
If the cost was in silver, divide its cost by 10.
If the cost was in gold, use the same number of gold pieces but they are now silver pieces.

\pagebreakNum

# Chapter 7: Mechanical Items
___
Operates differently from magic items. For one, they don't require attunement. Instead they are either free-to-use as needed (as non-attunement items are) or they have an internal cooldown mechanic specific to each item. Use the pyroconverger from Guildmaster's Guide to Ravnica for the model: 

> A Pyroconverger is an Izzet-made flamethrower. It carries a risk of malfunction each time you use it.
>
> As an action, you can cause the Pyroconverger to project fire in a 10-foot cone. Each creature in that area must make a DC 13 Dexterity saving throw, taking 4d6 fire damage on a failed save, or half as much damage on a successful one.
>
> Each time you use the Pyroconverger, roll a d10 and add the number of times you have used it since your last long rest. If the total is 11 or higher, the Pyroconverger malfunctions: you take 4d6 fire damage, and you can't use the Pyroconverger again until you finish a long rest.

The risk of malfunction may be higher or lower depending on the complexity and power of the item. The Tinker class may have the ability to push them even farther than normal.

Alternatively or in addition to the above model, they may require fuel to function. A goblin flame gun may require alchemist's fire, a mechanical squirrel may require phlogiston, etc.

